# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hardware-memory-safety
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hardware-memory-safety/bounds-checking] In computer programming, **bounds checking** is any method of detecting whether a variable is within some bounds before it is used.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/bounds-checking] It is usually used to ensure that a number fits into a given type (range checking), or that a variable being used as an array index is within the bounds of the array (index checking).
[src:hardware-memory-safety/bounds-checking] A failed bounds check usually results in the generation of some sort of exception signal.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/bounds-checking] As performing bounds checking during each use can be time-consuming, it is not always done.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/bounds-checking] Bounds-checking elimination is a compiler optimization technique that eliminates unneeded bounds checking.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/bounds-checking] A range check is a check to make sure a number is within a certain range; for example, to ensure that a value about to be assigned to a 16-bit integer is within the capacity of a 16-bit integer (i.e. checking against wrap-around).
[src:hardware-memory-safety/bounds-checking] This is not quite the same as type checking.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/bounds-checking] Other range checks may be more restrictive; for example, a variable to hold the number of a calendar month may be declared to accept only the range 1 to 12.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/bounds-checking] Index checking means that, in all expressions indexing an array, the index value is checked against the bounds of the array (which were established when the array was defined), and if the index is out-of-bounds, further execution is suspended via some sort of error.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/bounds-checking] Because reading or especially writing a value outside the bounds of an array may cause the program to malfunction or crash or enable security vulnerabilities (see buffer overflow), index checking is a part of many high-level languages.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/bounds-checking] Early compiled programming languages with index checking ability included ALGOL 60, ALGOL 68 and Pascal, as well as interpreted programming languages such as BASIC.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/bounds-checking] Many programming languages, such as C, never perform automatic bounds checking to raise speed.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/bounds-checking] However, this leaves many off-by-one errors and buffer overflows uncaught.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/bounds-checking] Many programmers believe these languages sacrifice too much for rapid execution.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/bounds-checking] Mainstream languages that enforce run time checking include Ada, C#, Haskell, Java, JavaScript, Lisp, PHP, Python, Ruby, Rust, and Visual Basic.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/bounds-checking] The D and OCaml languages have run time bounds checking that is enabled or disabled with a compiler switch.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/bounds-checking] In C++ run time checking is not part of the language, but part of the STL and is enabled with a compiler switch (_GLIBCXX_DEBUG=1 or _LIBCPP_DEBUG=1).
[src:hardware-memory-safety/bounds-checking] C# also supports *unsafe regions*: sections of code that (among other things) temporarily suspend bounds checking to raise efficiency.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/bounds-checking] These are useful for speeding up small time-critical bottlenecks without sacrificing the safety of a whole program.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/bounds-checking] The JS++ programming language is able to analyze if an array index or map key is out-of-bounds at compile time using existent types, which is a nominal type describing whether the index or key is within-bounds or out-of-bounds and guides code generation.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/bounds-checking] Existent types have been shown to add only 1ms overhead to compile times.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/bounds-checking] The safety added by bounds checking necessarily costs CPU time if the checking is performed in software; however, if the checks could be performed by hardware, then the safety can be provided "for free" with no runtime cost.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/bounds-checking] An early system with hardware bounds checking was the ICL 2900 Series mainframe announced in 1974.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/bounds-checking] The VAX computer has an INDEX assembly instruction for array index checking which takes six operands, all of which can use any VAX addressing mode.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/bounds-checking] The B6500 and similar Burroughs computers performed bound checking via hardware, irrespective of which computer language had been compiled to produce the machine code.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/bounds-checking] A limited number of later CPUs have specialised instructions for checking bounds, e.g., the CHK2 instruction on the Motorola 68000 series.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/bounds-checking] Research has been underway since at least 2005 regarding methods to use x86's built-in virtual memory management unit to ensure safety of array and buffer accesses.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/bounds-checking] In 2015 Intel provided their Intel MPX extensions in their Skylake processor architecture which stores bounds in a CPU register and table in memory.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/bounds-checking] As of early 2017 at least GCC supports MPX extensions.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-addressing] In computer science, **capability-based addressing** is a scheme used by some computers to control access to memory as an efficient implementation of capability-based security.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-addressing] Under a capability-based addressing scheme, pointers are replaced by protected objects (named **capabilities**) which specify both a location in memory, along with access rights which define the set of operations which can be carried out on the memory location.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-addressing] Capabilities can only be created or modified through the use of privileged instructions which may be executed only by either the kernel or some other privileged process authorised to do so.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-addressing] Thus, a kernel can limit application code and other subsystems access to the minimum necessary portions of memory (and disable write access where appropriate), without the need to use separate address spaces and therefore require a context switch when an access occurs.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-addressing] The System/38 supported two types of object pointer – *authorized pointers*, and *unauthorized pointers*, the former was the platform's implementation of capability-based addressing.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-addressing] Both types of pointer could only be manipulated using privileged instructions, and differed by whether object authorizations (i.e. access rights) were encoded in the contents of the pointer.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-addressing] Unauthorized pointers did not encode object authorizations, and required the operating system to check the object's authorization separately to determine if access to the object was allowed.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-addressing] Authorized pointers encoded object authorizations, meaning that possession of the pointer implied access, and the operating system was not required to verify authorization separately.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-addressing] Authorized pointers were irrevocable by design - if the object's authorizations were altered, it would not alter the encoded authorizations in any authorized pointers which already existed.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-addressing] Early versions of the OS/400 operating system for the AS/400 also supported authorized pointers, and by extension capability-based addressing.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-addressing] However, authorized pointers were removed in the V1R3 release of OS/400 as their irrevocable nature became seen as a security liability.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-addressing] All versions of OS/400 (later IBM i) since rely solely on unauthorized pointers which do not support capability-based addressing.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] A capability-based system, in contrast, is designed with that goal in mind.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] Capabilities achieve their objective of improving system security by being used in place of forgeable references.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] A forgeable reference (for example, a path name) identifies an object, but does not specify which access rights are appropriate for that object and the user program which holds that reference.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] Consequently, any attempt to access the referenced object must be validated by the operating system, based on the ambient authority of the requesting program, typically via the use of an access-control list (ACL).
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] Instead, in a system with capabilities, the mere fact that a user program possesses that capability entitles it to use the referenced object in accordance with the rights that are specified by that capability.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] In theory, a system with capabilities removes the need for any access control list or similar mechanism by giving all entities all and only the capabilities they will actually need.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] A capability is typically implemented as a privileged data structure that consists of a section that specifies access rights, and a section that uniquely identifies the object to be accessed.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] The user does not access the data structure or object directly, but instead via a handle.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] In practice, it is used much like a file descriptor in a traditional operating system (a traditional handle), but to access every object on the system.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] Capabilities are typically stored by the operating system in a list, with some mechanism in place to prevent the program from directly modifying the contents of the capability (so as to forge access rights or change the object it points to).
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] Some systems have also been based on capability-based addressing (hardware support for capabilities), such as Plessey System 250.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] Programs possessing capabilities can perform functions on them, such as passing them on to other programs, converting them to a less-privileged version, or deleting them.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] The operating system must ensure that only specific operations can occur to the capabilities in the system, in order to maintain the integrity of the security policy.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] Capabilities as discussed in this article should not be confused with Portable Operating System Interface (POSIX) 1e/2c "Capabilities".
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] The latter are coarse-grained privileges that cannot be transferred between processes.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] A capability is defined to be a protected object reference which, by virtue of its possession by a user process, grants that process the capability (hence the name) to interact with an object in certain ways.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] Those ways might include reading data associated with an object, modifying the object, executing the data in the object as a process, and other conceivable access rights.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] The capability logically consists of a reference that uniquely identifies a particular object and a set of one or more of these rights.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] Although this identifies a unique object on the system, it does not specify access rights and hence is not a capability.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] This pair identifies an object along with a set of access rights.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] The pair, however, is still not a capability because the user process's *possession* of these values says nothing about whether that access would actually be legitimate.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] The variable `fd` now contains the index of a file descriptor in the process's file descriptor table.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] Its existence in the process's file descriptor table is sufficient to show that the process does indeed have legitimate access to the object.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] A key feature of this arrangement is that the file descriptor table is in kernel memory and cannot be directly manipulated by the user program.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] In traditional operating systems, programs often communicate with each other and with storage using references like those in the first two examples.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] Path names are often passed as command-line parameters, sent via sockets, and stored on disk.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] These references are not capabilities, and must be validated before they can be used.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] In these systems, a central question is "on whose *authority* is a given reference to be evaluated?" This becomes a critical issue especially for processes which must act on behalf of two different authority-bearing entities.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] They become susceptible to a programming error known as the confused deputy problem, very frequently resulting in a security hole.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] In a capability-based system, the capabilities themselves are passed between processes and storage using a mechanism that is known by the operating system to maintain the integrity of those capabilities.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] One novel approach to solving this problem involves the use of an orthogonally persistent operating system.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] In such a system, there is no need for entities to be discarded and their capabilities be invalidated, and hence require an ACL-like mechanism to restore those capabilities at a later time.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] The operating system maintains the integrity and security of the capabilities contained within all storage, both volatile and nonvolatile, at all times; in part by performing all serialization tasks by itself, rather than requiring user programs to do so, as is the case in most operating systems.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] Because user programs are relieved of this responsibility, there is no need to trust them to reproduce only legal capabilities, nor to validate requests for access using an access control mechanism.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] An example implementation is the Flex machine from the early 1980s.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] Portable Operating System Interface (POSIX) draft 1003.1e specifies a concept of permissions called "capabilities".
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] However, POSIX capabilities differ from capabilities in this article.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] A POSIX capability is not associated with any object; a process having CAP_NET_BIND_SERVICE capability can listen on any TCP port under 1024.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] In contrast, Capsicum Unix hybridizes a true capability-system model with a Unix design and POSIX API.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] Capsicum capabilities are a refined form of file descriptor, a delegable right between processes and additional object types beyond classic POSIX, such as processes, can be referenced via capabilities.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] In Capsicum capability mode, processes are unable to utilize global namespaces (such as the filesystem namespace) to look up objects, and must instead inherit or be delegated them.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/capability-based-security] This system is found natively in FreeBSD, but patches are available to other systems.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] In computer science, **dynamic dispatch** is the process of selecting which implementation of a polymorphic operation (method or function) to call at run time.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] It is commonly employed in, and considered a prime characteristic of, object-oriented programming (OOP) languages and systems.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] Object-oriented systems model a problem as a set of interacting objects that enact operations referred to by name.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] Polymorphism is the phenomenon wherein somewhat interchangeable objects each expose an operation of the same name but possibly differing in behavior.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] As an example, a File object and a Database object both have a StoreRecord method that can be used to write a personnel record to storage.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] A program holds a reference to an object which may be either a File object or a Database object.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] Which one it is may have been determined by a run-time setting, and at this stage, the program may not know or care which.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] When the program calls StoreRecord on the object, something needs to choose which behavior gets enacted.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] If one thinks of OOP as sending messages to objects, then in this example the program sends a StoreRecord message to an object of unknown type, leaving it to the run-time support system to dispatch the message to the right object.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] The object enacts whichever behavior it implements.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] Dynamic dispatch contrasts with *static dispatch*, in which the implementation of a polymorphic operation is selected at compile time.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] The purpose of dynamic dispatch is to defer the selection of an appropriate implementation until the run time type of a parameter (or multiple parameters) is known.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] Dynamic dispatch is different from late binding (also known as dynamic binding).
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] Name binding associates a name with an operation.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] A polymorphic operation has several implementations, all associated with the same name.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] Bindings can be made at compile time or (with late binding) at run time.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] With dynamic dispatch, one particular implementation of an operation is chosen at run time.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] While dynamic dispatch does not imply late binding, late binding does imply dynamic dispatch, since the implementation of a late-bound operation is not known until run time.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] The choice of which version of a method to call may be based either on a single object, or on a combination of objects.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] The former is called *single dispatch* and is directly supported by common object-oriented languages such as Smalltalk, C++, Java, C#, Objective-C, Swift, JavaScript, and Python.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] This is thought of as sending a message named divide with parameter divisor to dividend.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] An implementation will be chosen based only on dividend's type (perhaps rational, floating point, matrix), disregarding the type or value of divisor.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] By contrast, some languages dispatch methods or functions based on the combination of operands; in the division case, the types of the dividend and divisor together determine which divide operation will be performed.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] Examples of languages that support multiple dispatch are Common Lisp, Dylan, and Julia.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] A language may be implemented with different dynamic dispatch mechanisms.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] The choices of the dynamic dispatch mechanism offered by a language to a large extent alter the programming paradigms that are available or are most natural to use within a given language.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] Normally, in a typed language, the dispatch mechanism will be performed based on the type of the arguments (most commonly based on the type of the receiver of a message).
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] Languages with weak or no typing systems often carry a dispatch table as part of the object data for each object.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] This allows **instance behaviour** as each instance may map a given message to a separate method.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] Dynamic dispatch will always incur an overhead so some languages offer static dispatch for particular methods.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] C++ uses early binding and offers both dynamic and static dispatch.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] To get dynamic dispatch the programmer must declare a method as virtual.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] C++ compilers typically implement dynamic dispatch with a data structure called a virtual function table (vtable) that defines the name-to-implementation mapping for a given class as a set of member function pointers.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] This is purely an implementation detail, as the C++ specification does not mention vtables.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] Instances of that type will then store a pointer to this table as part of their instance data, complicating scenarios when multiple inheritance is used.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] Since C++ does not support late binding, the virtual table in a C++ object cannot be modified at runtime, which limits the potential set of dispatch targets to a finite set chosen at compile time.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] Type overloading does not produce dynamic dispatch in C++ as the language considers the types of the message parameters part of the formal message name.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] This means that the message name the programmer sees is not the formal name used for binding.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] In Go, Rust and Nim, a more versatile variation of early binding is used.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] Vtable pointers are carried with object references as 'fat pointers' ('interfaces' in Go, or 'trait objects' in Rust).
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] This decouples the supported interfaces from the underlying data structures.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] Each compiled library needn't know the full range of interfaces supported in order to correctly use a type, just the specific vtable layout that they require.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] Code can pass around different interfaces to the same piece of data to different functions.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] This versatility comes at the expense of extra data with each object reference, which is problematic if many such references are stored persistently.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] The term *fat pointer* simply refers to a pointer with additional associated information.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] The additional information may be a vtable pointer for dynamic dispatch described above, but is more commonly the associated object's size to describe e.g. a *slice*.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] Smalltalk uses a type-based message dispatcher.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] Each instance has a single type whose definition contains the methods.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] When an instance receives a message, the dispatcher looks up the corresponding method in the message-to-method map for the type and then invokes the method.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] Because a type can have a chain of base types, this look-up can be expensive.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] A naive implementation of Smalltalk's mechanism would seem to have a significantly higher overhead than that of C++ and this overhead would be incurred for every message that an object receives.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] Real Smalltalk implementations often use a technique known as inline caching that makes method dispatch very fast.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] Inline caching basically stores the previous destination method address and object class of the call site (or multiple pairs for multi-way caching).
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] The cached method is initialized with the most common target method (or just the cache miss handler), based on the method selector.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] When the method call site is reached during execution, it just calls the address in the cache.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] A fast implementation may have multiple cache entries and it often only takes a couple of instructions to get execution to the correct method on an initial cache miss.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] The common case will be a cached class match, and execution will just continue in the method.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] Out-of-line caching can also be used in the method invocation logic, using the object class and method selector.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] In one design, the class and method selector are hashed, and used as an index into a method dispatch cache table.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] As Smalltalk is a reflective language, many implementations allow mutating individual objects into objects with dynamically generated method lookup tables.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] This allows altering object behavior on a per object basis.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] A whole category of languages known as prototype-based languages has grown from this, the most famous of which are Self and JavaScript.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] Careful design of the method dispatch caching allows even prototype-based languages to have high-performance method dispatch.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] Many other dynamically typed languages, including Python, Ruby, Objective-C and Groovy use similar approaches.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/fat-pointer] Dynamic dispatch is not built in to C like other languages, but it is still possible by manually managing function pointers.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] Segmentation refers to dividing a computer's memory into segments.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] A reference to a memory location includes a value that identifies a segment and an offset within that segment.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] A segment descriptor may limit access rights, e.g., read only, only from certain rings.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] The x86 architecture has multiple segmentation features, which are helpful for using protected memory on this architecture.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] On the x86 architecture, the Global Descriptor Table and Local Descriptor Tables can be used to reference segments in the computer's memory.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] Pointers to memory segments on x86 processors can also be stored in the processor's segment registers.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] Initially x86 processors had 4 segment registers, CS (code segment), SS (stack segment), DS (data segment) and ES (extra segment); later another two segment registers were added – FS and GS.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] In paging the memory address space or segment is divided into equal-sized blocks called pages.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] Using virtual memory hardware, each page can reside in any location at a suitable boundary of the computer's physical memory, or be flagged as being protected.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] Virtual memory makes it possible to have a linear virtual memory address space and to use it to access blocks fragmented over physical memory address space.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] Most computer architectures which support paging also use pages as the basis for memory protection.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] A *page table* maps virtual memory to physical memory.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] There may be a single page table, a page table for each process, a page table for each segment, or a hierarchy of page tables, depending on the architecture and the OS.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] The page tables are usually invisible to the process.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] Page tables make it easier to allocate additional memory, as each new page can be allocated from anywhere in physical memory.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] On some systems a page table entry can also designate a page as read-only.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] Some operating systems set up a different address space for each process, which provides hard memory protection boundaries.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] It is impossible for an unprivileged application to access a page that has not been explicitly allocated to it, because every memory address either points to a page allocated to that application, or generates an interrupt called a *page fault*.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] Unallocated pages, and pages allocated to any other application, do not have any addresses from the application point of view.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] A page fault may not necessarily indicate an error.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] Page faults are not only used for memory protection.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] The operating system may manage the page table in such a way that a reference to a page that has been previously paged out to secondary storage causes a page fault.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] The operating system intercepts the page fault, loads the required memory page, and the application continues as if no fault had occurred.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] This scheme, a type of virtual memory, allows in-memory data not currently in use to be moved to secondary storage and back in a way which is transparent to applications, to increase overall memory capacity.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] On some systems, a request for virtual storage may allocate a block of virtual addresses for which no page frames have been assigned, and the system will only assign and initialize page frames when page faults occur.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] On some systems a guard page may be used, either for error detection or to automatically grow data structures.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] On some systems, the page fault mechanism is also used for executable-space protection such as W^X.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] A memory protection key (MPK) mechanism divides physical memory into blocks of a particular size (e.g., 4 KiB), each of which has an associated numerical value called a protection key.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] Each process also has a protection key value associated with it.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] On a memory access the hardware checks that the current process's protection key matches the value associated with the memory block being accessed; if not, an exception occurs.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] This mechanism was introduced in the System/360 architecture.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] It is available on today's System z mainframes and heavily used by System z operating systems and their subsystems.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] The System/360 protection keys described above are associated with physical addresses.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] This is different from the protection key mechanism used by architectures such as the Hewlett-Packard/Intel IA-64 and Hewlett-Packard PA-RISC, which are associated with virtual addresses, and which allow multiple keys per process.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] In the Itanium and PA-RISC architectures, translations (TLB entries) have *keys* (Itanium) or *access ids* (PA-RISC) associated with them.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] A running process has several protection key registers (16 for Itanium, 4 for PA-RISC).
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] A translation selected by the virtual address has its key compared to each of the protection key registers.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] If any of them match (plus other possible checks), the access is permitted.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] If none match, a fault or exception is generated.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] The software fault handler can, if desired, check the missing key against a larger list of keys maintained by software; thus, the protection key registers inside the processor may be treated as a software-managed cache of a larger list of keys associated with a process.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] PA-RISC has 15–18 bits of key; Itanium mandates at least 18.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] Keys are usually associated with *protection domains*, such as libraries, modules, etc.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] In the x86, the protection keys architecture allows tagging virtual addresses for user pages with any of 16 protection keys.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] All the pages tagged with the same protection key constitute a protection domain.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] A new register contains the permissions associated with each of the protection domain.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] Load and store operations are checked against both the page table permissions and the protection key permissions associated with the protection domain of the virtual address, and only allowed if both permissions allow the access.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] The protection key permissions can be set from user space, allowing applications to directly restrict access to the application data without OS intervention.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] Since the protection keys are associated with a virtual address, the protection domains are per address space, so processes running in different address spaces can each use all 16 domains.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] In Multics and systems derived from it, each segment has a protection ring for reading, writing and execution; an attempt by a process with a higher ring number than the ring number for the segment causes a fault.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] There is a mechanism for safely calling procedures that run in a lower ring and returning to the higher ring.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] There are mechanisms for a routine running with a low ring number to access a parameter with the larger of its own ring and the caller's ring.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] Simulation is the use of a monitoring program to interpret the machine code instructions of some computer architectures.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] Such an instruction set simulator can provide memory protection by using a segmentation-like scheme and validating the target address and length of each instruction in real time before actually executing them.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] The simulator must calculate the target address and length and compare this against a list of valid address ranges that it holds concerning the thread's environment, such as any dynamic memory blocks acquired since the thread's inception, plus any valid shared static memory slots.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] The meaning of "valid" may change throughout the thread's life depending upon context.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] It may sometimes be allowed to alter a static block of storage, and sometimes not, depending upon the current mode of execution, which may or may not depend on a storage key or supervisor state.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] It is generally not advisable to use this method of memory protection where adequate facilities exist on a CPU, as this takes valuable processing power from the computer.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] Capability-based addressing is a method of memory protection that is unused in modern commercial computers.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] In this method, pointers are replaced by protected objects (called *capabilities*) that can only be created using privileged instructions which may only be executed by the kernel, or some other process authorized to do so.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] This effectively lets the kernel control which processes may access which objects in memory, with no need to use separate address spaces or context switches.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] Only a few commercial products used capability based security: Plessey System 250, IBM System/38, Intel iAPX 432 architecture and KeyKOS.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] Capability approaches are widely used in research systems such as EROS and Combex DARPA browser.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] They are used conceptually as the basis for some virtual machines, most notably Smalltalk and Java.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] Currently, the DARPA-funded CHERI project at University of Cambridge is working to create a modern capability machine that also supports legacy software.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] Dynamic tainting is a technique for protecting programs from illegal memory accesses.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] When memory is allocated, at runtime, this technique taints both the memory and the corresponding pointer using the same taint mark.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] Taint marks are then suitably propagated while the program executes and are checked every time a memory address *m* is accessed through a pointer *p*; if the taint marks associated with *m* and *p* differ, the execution is stopped and the illegal access is reported.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] SPARC M7 processors (and higher) implement dynamic tainting in hardware.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] Oracle markets this feature as Silicon Secured Memory (SSM) (previously branded as Application Data Integrity (ADI)).
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] The lowRISC CPU design includes dynamic tainting under the name Tagged Memory.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] The protection level of a particular implementation may be measured by how closely it adheres to the principle of minimum privilege.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] Different operating systems use different forms of memory protection or separation.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] Although memory protection was common on most mainframes and many minicomputer systems from the 1960s, true memory separation was not used in home computer operating systems until OS/2 (and in RISC OS) was released in 1987.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] On prior systems, such lack of protection was even used as a form of interprocess communication, by sending a pointer between processes.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] It is possible for processes to access System Memory in the Windows 9x family of operating systems.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/memory-protection] On Unix-like systems, the `mprotect` system call is used to control memory protection.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/tagged-architecture] Some early systems use tagging of data in memory but do not have all of the characteristics now considered to be part of tagged architectures.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/tagged-architecture] The RCA 601 has a 3-bit tag register and a 3-bit tag for every 24-bit half-word.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/tagged-architecture] Every instruction can request a test for equal or unequal tag, and cause a maskable interrupt if the specified match fails.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/tagged-architecture] There is no architectural connection between the tag and the contents of the half-word; it is strictly determined by the software.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/tagged-architecture] The Burroughs B5000, B5500 and B5700 have 48-bit words with no appended tag field.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/tagged-architecture] However, while there are no tag fields for character, instruction or numeric (floating point) words, all of the control word formats include a 3-bit tag.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/tagged-architecture] The Burroughs B6500 and its successors have a 3-bit tag for every word.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/tagged-architecture] In contrast, program and data memory are indistinguishable in the von Neumann architecture, making the way the memory is referenced critical to interpret the correct meaning.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/tagged-architecture] Notable examples of American tagged architectures were the Lisp machines, which had tagged pointer support at the hardware and opcode level, the Burroughs B6500 and successors, which have a data-driven tagged and descriptor-based architecture, and the non-commercial Rice Computer.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/tagged-architecture] Both the Burroughs and Lisp machine are examples of high-level language computer architectures, where the tagging is used to support types from a high-level language at the hardware level.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/tagged-architecture] In addition to this, the original Xerox Smalltalk implementation used the least-significant bit of each 16-bit word as a tag bit: if it was clear then the hardware would accept it as an aligned memory address while if it was set it was treated as a (shifted) 15-bit integer.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/tagged-architecture] Current Intel documentation mentions that the lower bits of a memory address might be similarly used by some interpreter-based systems.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/tagged-architecture] In the Soviet Union, the Elbrus series of supercomputers pioneered the use of tagged architectures in 1973.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/tagged-architecture] The RISC-V J extension and memory-tagging extension (Zimt) both propose adding some support for tagged architecture at the instruction level.
[src:hardware-memory-safety/tagged-architecture] CHERI (Capability Hardware Enhanced RISC Instructions) uses a tagged architecture to add capability-based addressing to several existing ISAs such as x86, MIPS, and RISC-V.
